In [[archaeology]], a '''bout-coupé''' is a type of [[handaxe]] that constituted part of the [[Neanderthal]] [[Mousterian]] [[archaeological industry|industry]] of the [[Middle Palaeolithic]]. The handaxes are bifacially-worked and in the shape of a rounded triangle.

They are only found in [[Great Britain|Britain]] in the [[Marine Isotope Stage]] 3 (MIS 3) interglacial between 59,000 and 41,000 years BP, and are therefore considered a unique diagnostic variant.<ref>{{cite book|title=The British Palaeolithic: Human Societies at the Edge of the Pleistocene World|first1=Paul|last1=Pettitt|first2=Mark|last2=White|publisher=Routledge|year=2012|page=349|location=Abingdon, UK|isbn=978-0-415-67455-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1468-0092.00152/abstract|author=White, Mark J|author2=Jacobi, Roger M|title=Two Sides to Every Story: Bout Coupé Handaxes Revisited|date=May 2002|publisher=Wiley Online Library|journal=Oxford Journal of Archaeology|volume=21|issue=2|doi=10.1111/1468-0092.00152|pages=109–133}}</ref>

